title: Fix build for Python 3.8
body:
**Description**:
This patch fixes build on Python 3.8 by replacing deprecated `linux_distribution` with `get_linux_distro()`, which reads [`/etc/os-release`](http://manpages.ubuntu.com/manpages/xenial/man5/os-release.5.html).

**Motivation and Context**
- `platform.linux_distribution` is deprecated since Python 3.5 and removed in Python 3.8
- This fixes #2664

title: Reduce BFCArena::FindChunkPtr::kMaxInternalFragmentation.
body:
**Description**: 
Currently we prevent 128MB chunks of memory from the largest bin from being split due to kMaxInternalFragmentation. 
kMaxInternalFragmentation doesn't affect the smaller bins as the test is that the remaining size is > 128MB, and only the largest bin 
(second largest has max of 128MB, so remaining will always be less than 128MB) can possibly satisfy that.

Code involved:

```
void* BFCArena::FindChunkPtr(BinNum bin_num, size_t rounded_bytes, size_t num_bytes) {
  // First identify the first bin that could satisfy rounded_bytes.
  for (; bin_num < kNumBins; bin_num++) {
      ...
      if (chunk->size >= rounded_bytes) {
        ...
        // If we can break the size of the chunk into two reasonably large
        // pieces, do so.  In any case don't waste more than
        // kMaxInternalFragmentation bytes on padding this alloc.
-->     const int64_t kMaxInternalFragmentation = 128 << 20;  // 128mb
        if (chunk->size >= rounded_bytes * 2 ||
-->         static_cast<int64_t>(chunk->size) - rounded_bytes >= kMaxInternalFragmentation) {
          SplitChunk(h, rounded_bytes);
          chunk = ChunkFromHandle(h);  // Update chunk pointer in case it moved
        }
```

We don't prevent breaking any other sized chunk based on kMaxInternalFragmentation, so having a 128+ MB chunk unused seems to be of no meaningful value.

Changing the max to 1MB provides significant overall memory usage savings. Debug output about memory allocations from an arbitrary production model:

128MB kMaxInternalFragmentation |  |  |  |  | 
-- | -- | -- | -- | -- | --
Bin size |  | In-use/Total |  |  |  |  | 
256 | Chunks | 1/1 | Bytes | 256/256 | Requested | 8 | 
512 | Chunks | 1/1 | Bytes | 512/512 | Requested | 496 | 
1024 | Chunks | 1/1 | Bytes | 1024/1024 | Requested | 992 | 
4096 | Chunks | 1/1 | Bytes | 4864/4864 | Requested | 4864 | 
4194304 | Chunks | 1/1 | Bytes | 8192000/8192000 | Requested | 8192000 | 
8388608 | Chunks | 1/1 | Bytes | 12288000/12288000 | Requested | 12288000 | 
67108864 | Chunks | 1/1 | Bytes | 112780800/112780800 | Requested | 73728000 | 
134217728 | Chunks | 1/1 | Bytes | 135168000/135168000 | Requested | 77824000 | 
268435456 | Chunks | 2/2 | Bytes | 805306368/805306368 | Requested | 623770112 | 
Diff between   in-use and requested bytes is 277933352 |  |  | 
 |  |  |  |  |  |  | 
1MB   kMaxInternalFragmentation |  |  |  |  | 
256 | Chunks | 1/1 | Bytes | 256/256 | Requested | 8 | 
512 | Chunks | 1/1 | Bytes | 512/512 | Requested | 496 | 
1024 | Chunks | 1/1 | Bytes | 1024/1024 | Requested | 992 | 
4096 | Chunks | 1/1 | Bytes | 4864/4864 | Requested | 4864 | 
4194304 | Chunks | 1/1 | Bytes | 8192000/8192000 | Requested | 8192000 | 
8388608 | Chunks | 1/1 | Bytes | 12288000/12288000 | Requested | 12288000 | 
33554432 | Chunks | 0/1 | Bytes | 0/59539200 | Requested | 0 | New
67108864 | Chunks | 1/4 | Bytes | 102400000/369945856 | Requested | 102400000 | 3 extra chunks here
134217728 | Chunks | 1/1 | Bytes | 185926144/185926144 | Requested | 185926144 | 
268435456 | Chunks | 1/1 | Bytes | 437843968/437843968 | Requested | 437843968 | 
Diff between   in-use and requested bytes is 296 |  |  |  | 

265MB of memory was saved by allowing breaking up allocations from the largest bin. 

**Motivation and Context**
Reduce wasted memory usage.

title: MLAS: update SGEMM threading parameters
body:
**Description**: Update the defines used to control SGEMM threading.

**Motivation and Context**
The old code was still structured to handle the Win32 thread pool where there was a high cost to starting a new work item, hence the number of items to be fmadd'ed was coarser. This value is no longer appropriate when using the Eigen threadpool. Updated to use the same value as OpenMP which in ad hoc tests yields good performance (certainly better than before). @snnn ran a performance test and most models were neutral (where GEMMs were already large) and a few models were significantly faster (where some GEMMs now use more threads).

title: speed up Windows TRT CI
body:
currently the CI for Windows TensorRT can take up to 1 hour 50 minutes.
longer term will refactor the CI, but for now there are some improvements that can be made to speed things up significantly.
- don't run onnx tests with CUDA provider when building TRT provider. (saves about 10 minutes)
- remove unneeded build options/tests (dnnl, csharp, gen_doc)
- split debug and release jobs so they can be run in parallel.

with these changes, the debug build takes 30 min and release 47 min. so it can take 47 min when jobs run in parallel.
see https://dev.azure.com/onnxruntime/onnxruntime/_build/results?buildId=107001&view=results

title: Upgrade gtest to the latest version
body:
**Description**: 

Upgrade gtest to the latest version. However, because the newer version hit a bug in gcc, even though the bug is already fixed in the latest gcc version but we're using gcc 4.8.x and we can't change that,  so we have to do a compromise,  change our code a little bit to make it work.

Background:
<hr/>
From: Tiago 

Hi Changming, I'm looking at the Linux pipeline build failure with latest googletest. It's hitting this GCC bug: https://gcc.gnu.org/bugzilla/show_bug.cgi?id=51213 in this template: https://github.com/google/googletest/compare/9bda90b7e5e08c4c37a832d0cea218aed6af6470...703bd9caab50b139428cea1aaff9974ebee5742e#diff-92131a3467c5f3247170faff2fa23c25L886-R898 .
 
Basically, they use a template overload with SFINAE to detect whether an object is iterable:
```c++
template <class C,
          class Iterator = decltype(::std::declval<const C&>().begin()),
          class = decltype(::std::declval<const C&>().end()),
          class = decltype(++::std::declval<Iterator&>()),
          class = decltype(*::std::declval<Iterator>()),
          class = typename C::const_iterator>
IsContainer IsContainerTest(int /* dummy */) { 
```
The bug is that decltype(::std::declval<const C&>().begin()) makes GCC throw an invalid access instead of picking the next template overload if the class has begin(), but from a private inheritance (so if the member exists but is not accessible, GCC fails with "error: A is not an accessible base of B" instead of trying the next template overload). This was a bug in GCC.
<hr/>


**Motivation and Context**
- Why is this change required? What problem does it solve?
WinML would like to update the googletest submodule. They want some newer features (namely GTEST_SKIP to skip tests programmatically and be able to skip entire fixtures easily) and would need to update the submodule version.

- If it fixes an open issue, please link to the issue here.

title: Move memory info into IAllocator
body:
**Description**: 
  - Update the IAllocator setup to move the OrtMemoryInfo to the base class instead of requiring derived classes to have that as a member and override a virtual method to return it.
  - Cleanup CreateAllocator setup to take an argument as to whether to wrap the device allocator in an arena allocator.

  - Add ability to disable using an arena for CUDA allocations for consistency with what's allowed for the CPU allocations

  - Minor cleanups in the various EPs to adjust to the change to IAllocator and CreateAllocator, and to use the create_area flag consistently when available.
  - Move DummyArena to test code. It shouldn't be needed by any production code anymore.

**Motivation and Context**
Initial motivation was adding the ability to disable the arena for CUDA allocations for consistency. In making that change the confusing setup around how/when an arena allocator wrapped the device allocator led to the IAllocator changes.

title: Optimize BatchNormalization to NCHWc Conv
body:
**Description**: Update the NCHWc transformer to convert BatchNormalization ops to NCHWc convolutions when the input tensor is already in NCHWc.

**Motivation and Context**
CNNs such as resnet50v2 and densenets have architectures where the blocks are arranged as BatchNormalization+Relu+Conv. The NCHWc transformer didn't have support for the leading BatchNormalization node, so the graph would be run with extra reorder ops that hurt performance. 

This change teaches the optimizer to rewrite the BatchNormalization as a depthwise 1x1 convolution when the input tensor is already in NCHWc format. I did it this way to avoid adding another com.microsoft.nchwc op that does the plain scale/bias. A little more performance could be squeezed out by special casing this path inside MLAS. Doing it this way also allowed the existing NchwcConv+Relu fusion to automatically work.

The model zoo version of resnet50v2 goes from 29->21ms on one system with 126->75 nodes.

body:
**Description**: 
InferenceSession::Run needs to call OnRunEnd for any EP that OnRunStart was called for so they can cleanup. Currently it only calls OnRunEnd if the Status is OK. Due to this, if graph execution failed the CUDA EP will throw during shutdown as the per-thread information has not been cleaned up prior to the CUDA library shutting down.

Also update onnxruntime_perf_test to catch the exception from the call to Run and return a Status. Otherwise it exits with an 'unknown exception' error.

**Motivation and Context**
Whilst the exception from graph execution is gracefully returned as a Status, the issue with OnRunEnd not being called leads to an unhandled exception during shutdown.

title: User/sheilk/winml adapter c api
body:
Description
1. Make the winml adapter api a c-abi that uses/enhances the onnxruntime c-abi.
2. Extend OrtTypeInfo to create Map and Sequence Info objects in the adapter.
3. Create the DML provider with the dml provider factory in the adapter, rather than on our own.
4. Move WinRT completely out of the adapter.
5. Isolate all onnx/ort calls into the ort static library that lives in the winml dll.
6. Make Map and Sequence do the minimum number of copies while still using the c-abi. This involves implementing the map and sequence types on the c-abi instead of the cxx apis.
7. Make the winml adapter dependent on the ort_api version.
8. Dont use globals to access the winml adapter, as we may want to create multiple engines concurrently with different ort versions in the future.
9. Use the c-abi directly, to prevent adding another projection layer between winml and ort.
10. Isolate all dml api calls in the ort lib, so that DML is just an implementation detail of the onnxruntime engine implementation, and not a detail of the winrt projection. WinML is now only aware of dx devices and d3d11/12 resources.
